Well boys you are bound to hear it sooner or later, and I would rather it come from me. Sami died from a toxic combination of drugs.

In the next few days Iâm going to be hearing a lot from well-intentioned people about what a great guy my brother was, and I want to be clear with people I care about how I actually feel:

Sami was a degenerate junkie, a malignant narcissist, and a sexual predator.  

The tragedy of him dying so young doesnât change the fact that when he was alive, he hurt a lot of people. Good people. People who didnât deserve to get lied to, assaulted, robbed, or taken advantage of.

No doubt lots of folks who didnât know him as well as I did will be busting out of the woodwork to say that all the terrible shit he did wasnât a reflection on him, because âaddiction is a diseaseâ.  I guess itâs less painful to believe that than to be honest about who he was.

The reality is that Sami was a profoundly selfish and emotionally unstable person before he ever took his first drink or snorted his first line. 

His substance abuse was simply one manifestation of a personality that lacked any kind of self control or recognition that actions have consequences. Itâs taken me a lot of years and a lot of tears to come to terms with that.  

I love him, but I donât think he loved me. I donât believe he had the capacity to truly love anyone but himself.

He has been dead to me since 2015, when he told me if I ever mentioned rehab again he would kill himself and it would be my fault. 

Years after that, we repaired our friendship, but from that day onward there was no doubt in my mind that this day would come sooner rather than later.

I made peace with our complicated relationship, and his death, a long time ago. I hope everyone else who had the unique pleasure and heartbreak of knowing him can make peace with it some day. But they should make peace with the man that he was, not the man we all wanted him to be.

Section I: Historical Context of The Troubles
 
            The 19th century of world history was the British century. Great Britain was the first country to undergo the Industrial Revolution, a technological quantum leap forward in production capabilities, scientific knowledge, transportation, and communication. This coupled with their naval superiority led to their conquest and economic subjugation of a vast portion of the planet. As the saying went, âThe sun never sets on the British Empire.â
But by the turn of the 20th century, the sun was in fact setting on the British Empire. The cracks were beginning to show in their colonial holdings, and from India to Nigeria the local people were developing a sense of nationalism and questioning why they should be ruled by faraway people with no connection to their culture. But the British colonial empire was not limited to occupation of faraway lands with no ability to project violence against the British homeland. They also governed the neighboring island of Ireland, an area with which they shared no small amount of cultural connection and a long, violent history. The rifts between these peoples were longstanding; the British had converted to various forms of Protestantism since the Renaissance era, while for the most part the Irish remained a staunchly Catholic polity. In the 1840âs the British government presided over the Irish Potato famine, a largely manmade food shortage that led to the mass exodus of Irish and the death of many who remained.  The English themselves justified this dominance structure with an ideology of ethnoreligious supremacy that painted non-English people as inferior to them and the beneficiaries of their enlightened custodianship. The Irish were no exception.
This came to a head in the early 20th century. Following the First World War in 1918, in which many Irish and other colonial provincials fought, the Irish Republican Army was formed. This fractious group believed it was justified in using violence to achieve their political goals, often against the British occupiers, but also against noncombatants, and each other. From 1919 to 1921, they fought a bloody war of independence for Ireland, which culminated in the Anglo-Irish Treaty of 1921, which partitioned Ireland into the independent south with Dublin as its capital, and the British controlled (and largely Protestant) North which had its capital in Belfast. For many members of the IRA, this was an untenable peace, and the organization splintered almost immediately into pragmatists like Michael Collins who were in support of the treaty and radicals like Eamon de Valera who would accept nothing less than a unified Irish Republic. Collins became the governor of the new southern state but was subsequently assassinated by IRA members in 1922. It was clear that while the Irish War of Independence had been formally concluded, the grievances and impetus for continued violence had not been adjudicated.
 
Section II: The Major Players
            The obvious status quo power of this conflict was the British. They desired to continue their colonial dominance of Ireland and viewed their state-sponsored violence as law enforcement rather than an offensive war of occupation. Less obvious are the Protestant and otherwise pro-Unionist Irish. They did not wish to see a change to the status quo, perhaps justifiably fearing the reprisal of their bitter Catholic and Republican countrymen as punishment for their perceived complicity in the colonial regime.  The opposition group was the IRA, in its varied incarnations. Though not always cohesive ideologically, the IRAâs non-state paramilitary status and disruptive nature made them natural foes of established laws, norms, and political hierarchies.
 
Section III: How Did the IRA Justify Violence?
The IRAâs coalescence as an opposition group did not occur in a vacuum. There was a combination of internal and external influences that informed their conception of who they were, who their enemies were, and what had to be done. The combined forces of new ideologies like Nationalism: the belief in self-determination for defined group, Marxism: the belief that political society is defined by the struggle between the oppressed and their oppressors, and old forces like Catholic sectarianism made violence the inevitable conclusion of the IRAâs belief system.
They viewed the status quo itself as violence: the robbery of the Irish national economy, the denial of their right to govern themselves, the suppression of their faith, even the supplanting of their national language, Gaelic, were all the ill-gotten goods of violent conquest and continued British military supremacy. To the IRA the British were robbing them not only of the freedoms that all people were due, but also of what it meant to be Irish. My name is Cameron Keyani, class of 2016. I write to you as a former Chair of the Student Conduct Board, a former Student Ambassador for the Center for the Study of Democracy, and a former member of the Sexual Misconduct Advocacy and Resource Team. But mostly, I write to you as a concerned alumnus of St. Maryâs. While I speak only for myself, I can assure you that I do not represent a fringe dissenting opinion among my fellow alumni.

I have been concerned, during my time in school and since my graduation, that my beloved St. Maryâs is losing itâs way. St. Maryâs was once well known as a party school, and in recent years has made understandable attempts to distance itself from that reputation and rebrand as a more serious academic institution. Change is never easy, and I applaud this difficult endeavor. What I cannot countenance, and what I can assure you will not achieve its intended goals, is diverting institutional resources and focus away from educating young minds, and towards micromanaging campus life.

The new campus policy for open containers, open invitation parties, and loud music is just the latest excess of an administration and public safety service that is obsessed with enforcing a puritanical vision of morality and respectability on campus. They will claim that this new policy, and their increased authority on campus, is for the âsafetyâ and âbest interestâ of the students. Yet during my 4 years on the Conduct Board, the most consistent threat to the safety and best interest of students was in fact  Public Safety, with their violent, cavalier attitude towards enforcement, their egregious mishandling of sexual misconduct cases, and their obsession with documenting students for victimless infractions of college code. This changed for the better in the years following the firing of Sean Tallarico, but the school now seems determined to return to those dark days.

I can promise you that giving PS increased power to regulate campus activity will not make anyone safer. It will only overload the conduct system with violators, impoverish campus life, and divert crucial resources that would be better spent on the salaries of our incredible professors, food services, custodial, counseling, and groundskeeping staff.

No matter what changes come, I will never stop loving and cherishing the memories I have at St. Maryâs. The St. Maryâs Way follows me everywhere I go, and I know how incredibly lucky I am to have spent my formative years to such an open and loving campus, with such a vibrant student body. 

However, as long as the administration is determined to go down the path they have been on, of infantilizing students with a campus police state instead of treating them as adults who can,and must, make their own mistakes; as long as the administration thinks a worthwhile application of its resources is buying Dodge Chargers for PS rather than bringing Adjunct professors on as tenured staff; as long as this state of affairs continues, I can promise you that myself and like-minded peers will not be donating a single cent to our beloved alma mater. Not for a lack of appreciation for what the school gave to us, but for the near certainty that our money will be wasted on pointless, misguided endeavors.

Very Respectfully,

Cameron Keyani

A Dangerous Conflation: Freedom of Speech is Not Freedom From Consequences

Despite entire careers built on leveling this criticism at the left, the reactionary right seems to fundamentally misunderstand what Freedom of Speech is, and the rights that it confers.

The First Amendment of the Constitution says: 

âCongress shall make now law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or of the right of people to peaceably assemble, and to petition the Government for a redress of these grievancesâ

If a news anchor launches into a racist tirade on air, and the network executives decide to fire her due to fears of lower ratings, no oneâs right to free speech has been violated. 

Similarly, if an employee uses homophobic slurs around the water cooler that make his gay colleagues feel uncomfortable and unwelcome in the workplace, his firing does not represent the totalitarian tyranny of political correctness, merely the enforcement of the legal waivers addressing workplace harassment and discrimination that he willingly signed when he accepted his job. 

The First Amendment protects you from imprisonment and persecution by state authorities for voicing your opinion and how you choose to worship. It does not protect you from being ostracized by your peers for voicing opinions that are hateful or stupid. It does not protect you from employers who can prove that your opinions are causing a disruptive and hostile workplace environment. And for public figures, it certainly does not give you the right to voice your opinion free from criticism, protest, and boycotts.  

None of these scenarios represent any limitation of civil rights or freedom of expression, simply shifting cultural norms. Many attitudes that might have been considered acceptable in the 1950s are now viewed as profoundly racist,sexist, and homophobic. I personally would argue that, on balance, this cultural change has been a good thing, but Iâm open to debate on that assessment.  What is not up for debate is that the limitations these changing societal values have put on expressing oneself have in no way undercut the legal protections guaranteed by the First Amendment.

What an outrageous irony, then, that in spouting alarmist rhetoric about the âattack on free speechâ  cultural commentators like Jordan Peterson and Ben Shapiro are fabricating exactly the kind of hysterical self-victimization narratives that they accuse progressives, feminists, and advocates for racial equality of engaging in.

To be clear, black-clad Antifa enacting the hecklerâs veto by attacking public speaking events of right wing figures like Milo Yanopolis and Ann Coulter on college campuses is an attack on free speech. I would also argue it reflects poorly on conservative student groups that they would choose to invite speakers whose only claim to fame is being bigoted agent provocateurs. But they have the right to do so, and on publicly-funded campuses the far left doesnât get unilateral authority to decide who can voice their opinion.

Private organizations, however, are entitled to spend their money and associate with who they choose. A private company like Twitter can decide they no longer want to host a bigot like Yanopolis on their platform and delete his account, all without violating anyoneâs Constitutional rights. I believe this minutiae has been lost on many people.

I think there can be salient arguments against unrestricted free speech. Countries across Europe have criminalized Holocaust denial, in an attempt to come to grips with that chilling history and prevent revisionists from trying to minimize it. I donât think this makes these countries significantly less free than America.

But personally, I would not support laws like these in Americaâ I believe we should allow the greatest degree of free speech that can coexist with public safety. Yet freedom without responsibility has no value. 

Yes, you CAN walk into a public park with an SS Officer uniform on, but you probably shouldnât. And if you do choose to make that horrible, horrible decision, you DEFINITELY shouldnât pretend that old Jewish grandma in the park is violating your rights when she doesnât let you pet her dog.

First is the Islamic Republic of Iran and their associated Shiite state and non-state actors in the Arab world like Hezbollah and the Houthis of Yemen. They are one of the few state actors that is open about their opposition to the US-led world order, which makes them a natural ally to Russia. Second is the Jewish state of Israel, who enjoy a close relationship with the United States buttressed by a generous military and economic aid relationship, as well as hostile relations with most of the states on their border. Third are the Sunni fundamentalist groups such as al-Qaeda, Muslim Brotherhood, al-Nusra Islamic State. Though they are not recognized by multilateral organizations, the Islamic State in particular has been able to control large portions of Syria and Iraq and wield the power of a state actor. Finally, are the more moderate Sunni regimes: Egypt, Jordan, Turkey, and the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) countries. They are a fractious and loosely knit group, but their interests line up in terms of their opposition to Sunni fundamentalist non-state actors and Iran, as well as their military cooperation with the United States. It is a very dangerous neighborhood that includes some of the southern portions of the Caucasus mountain range.
